[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:mutation-observer/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] The `MutationObserver` method **`observe()`** configures the `MutationObserver` callback to begin receiving notifications of changes to the DOM that match the given options.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Depending on the configuration, the observer may watch a single `Node` in the DOM tree, or that node and some or all of its descendant nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] The same node can be observed by multiple observers, and the same `MutationObserver` can watch for changes to different parts of the DOM tree and/or different types of changes by calling `observe()` multiple times on the same `MutationObserver`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] To stop the `MutationObserver` (so that none of its callbacks will be triggered any longer), call `MutationObserver.disconnect()`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] A DOM `Node` (which may be an `Element`) within the DOM tree to watch for changes, or to be the root of a subtree of nodes to be watched.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] An object providing options that describe which DOM mutations should be reported to `mutationObserver`'s `callback`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] At a minimum, one of `childList`, `attributes`, and/or `characterData` must be `true` when you call `observe()`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Otherwise, a `TypeError` exception will be thrown.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Set to `true` to extend monitoring to the entire subtree of nodes rooted at `target`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] All of the other properties are then extended to all of the nodes in the subtree instead of applying solely to the `target` node.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Note that if a descendant of `target` is removed, changes in that descendant subtree will continue to be observed, until the notification about the removal itself has been delivered.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Set to `true` to monitor the target node (and, if `subtree` is `true`, its descendants) for the addition of new child nodes or removal of existing child nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Set to `true` to watch for changes to the value of attributes on the node or nodes being monitored.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] The default value is `true` if either of `attributeFilter` or `attributeOldValue` is specified, otherwise the default value is `false`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] An array of specific attribute names to be monitored.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] If this property isn't included, changes to all attributes cause mutation notifications.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Set to `true` to record the previous value of any attribute that changes when monitoring the node or nodes for attribute changes; See Monitoring attribute values for an example of watching for attribute changes and recording values.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Set to `true` to monitor the specified target node (and, if `subtree` is `true`, its descendants) for changes to the character data contained within the node or nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] The default value is `true` if `characterDataOldValue` is specified, otherwise the default value is `false`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Set to `true` to record the previous value of a node's text whenever the text changes on nodes being monitored.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] In this example, we demonstrate how to call the method **`observe()`** on an instance of `MutationObserver`, once it has been set up, passing it a target element and an `options` object.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] If you watch a node using the `subtree` option, you will continue to receive notifications of changes to the descendants of the node, even after a part of the subtree is removed.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] However, once the notification about the removal is delivered, further changes to the detached subtree will no longer trigger the observer.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] This prevents you from missing changes that occur after the connection is severed and before you have a chance to specifically begin monitoring the moved node or subtree for changes.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Theoretically, this means that if you keep track of the `MutationRecord` objects describing the changes that occur, you should be able to "undo" the changes, rewinding the DOM back to its initial state.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] In this example, a Mutation Observer is set up to watch for changes to the `status` and `username` attributes in any elements contained within a subtree that displays the names of users in a chat room.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] This lets the code, for example, reflect changes to users' nicknames, or to mark them as away from keyboard (AFK) or offline.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] In this example we observe an element for attribute value changes, and add a button which toggles the element's `dir` attribute between `"ltr"` and `"rtl"`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver-observe] Inside the observer's callback, we log the old value of the attribute.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] The **`MutationObserver`** interface provides the ability to watch for changes being made to the DOM tree.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] It is designed as a replacement for the older Mutation Events feature, which was part of the DOM3 Events specification.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] Creates and returns a new `MutationObserver` which will invoke a specified callback function when DOM changes occur.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] Stops the `MutationObserver` instance from receiving further notifications until and unless `observe()` is called again.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] Configures the `MutationObserver` to begin receiving notifications through its callback function when DOM changes matching the given options occur.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] Removes all pending notifications from the `MutationObserver`'s notification queue and returns them in a new `Array` of `MutationRecord` objects.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationobserver] The following example was adapted from this blog post.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] The **`MutationRecord`** is a read-only interface that represents an individual DOM mutation observed by a `MutationObserver`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] It is the object inside the array passed to the callback of a `MutationObserver`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] Will be an empty `NodeList` if no nodes were added.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] The name of the changed attribute as a string, or `null`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] The namespace of the changed attribute as a string, or `null`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] The next sibling of the added or removed nodes, or `null`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] The previous sibling of the added or removed nodes, or `null`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] Will be an empty `NodeList` if no nodes were removed.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] The node the mutation affected, depending on the `MutationRecord.type`.
[src:mutation-observer/mutationrecord] A string representing the type of mutation: `attributes` if the mutation was an attribute mutation, `characterData` if it was a mutation to a `CharacterData` node, and `childList` if it was a mutation to the tree of nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:mutation-observer/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
